State in <a href="/wiki/Lepus3" title="Lepus3">LePUS3</a> (<a href="http://lepus.org.uk/ref/legend/legend.xml" class="external text" title="http://lepus.org.uk/ref/legend/legend.xml" rel="nofollow">legend</a>)</div>
</div>
</div>
<p>The <b>state pattern</b> is a <a href="/wiki/Behavioral_pattern" title="Behavioral pattern">behavioral</a> <a href="/wiki/Software_design_pattern" title="Software design pattern" class="mw-redirect">software design pattern</a>, also known as the <b>objects for states pattern</b>. This pattern is used in <a href="/wiki/Computer_programming" title="Computer programming">computer programming</a> to represent the state of an <a href="/wiki/Object_(computer_science)" title="Object (computer science)">object</a>. This is a clean way for an object to partially change its type at runtime<sup id="cite_ref-GangOfFour_0-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-GangOfFour-0" title=""><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup>.</p>
<p>Take for example, a drawing program, in which there could be an <a href="/wiki/Abstract_interface" title="Abstract interface" class="mw-redirect">abstract interface</a> representing a tool, then <a href="/wiki/Concrete_instance" title="Concrete instance" class="mw-redirect">concrete instances</a> of that class could each represent a kind of tool. When the user selects a different tool, the appropriate tool would be <a href="/wiki/Instance_(programming)" title="Instance (programming)" class="mw-redirect">instantiated</a>.</p>
